[2026-03-09T21:13:29Z] [llm] {"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01C4BCGJh54tUdSBFVekTnrm","type":"tool_result","content":"     1â†’# Workflows\n     2â†’\n     3â†’Cloche workflows define a directed graph of steps connected by named results.\n     4â†’\n     5â†’## Workflow Locations\n     6â†’\n     7â†’Cloche distinguishes two workflow locations based on the file they live in:\n     8â†’\n     9â†’**Container workflows** (`.cloche/*.cloche` except `host.cloche`) â€” Run inside a Docker\n    10â†’container via `cloche-agent`. Steps may only be `agent` or `script` type. These are the\n    11â†’standard workflows for coding tasks.\n    12â†’\n    13â†’**Host workflow** (`.cloche/host.cloche`) â€” Runs on the host machine as the daemon\n    14â†’process. Steps may be `agent`, `script`, or `workflow` type. The `workflow` step type\n    15â†’dispatches a container workflow run and waits for it to complete. This is the extension\n    16â†’point for custom orchestration strategies.\n    17â†’\n    18â†’The convention is enforced at parse time: a `workflow_name` step in a container workflow\n    19â†’file is a parse error.\n    20â†’\n    21â†’## Concepts\n    22â†’\n    23â†’| Concept  | Description                                                        |\n    24â†’|----------|--------------------------------------------------------------------|\n    25â†’| workflow | A named graph of steps connected by result wiring                  |\n    26â†’| step     | A unit of work (inferred: `prompt` = agent, `run` = script)        |\n    27â†’| result   | A named outcome reported by a step (e.g. \"success\", \"fail\")       |\n    28â†’| wiring   | Maps a step's result to the next step                              |\n    29â†’| done     | Built-in terminal step â€” successful completion                     |\n    30â†’| abort    | Built-in terminal step â€” failure with error reporting              |\n    31â†’\n    32â†’## Step Types\n    33â†’\n    34â†’Step type is inferred from the fields present in the step body:\n    35â†’\n    36â†’**agent** (has `prompt`) â€” Invokes a coding agent (Claude Code, or any tool conforming\n    37â†’to the agent adapter interface) with a prompt. The agent works autonomously inside the\n    38â†’container. Available in both host and container workflows.\n    39â†’\n    40â†’**script** (has `run`) â€” Runs a shell command. Used for tests, linters, validators, or\n    41â†’any deterministic check. Available in both host and container workflows.\n    42â†’\n    43â†’**workflow** (has `workflow_name`) â€” Dispatches a named container workflow run and blocks\n    44â†’until it completes. Only available in host workflows (`host.cloche`).\n    45â†’\n    46â†’A step with more than one of `prompt`, `run`, or `workflow_name`, or none of them, is a\n    47â†’parse error.\n    48â†’\n    49â†’## DSL Syntax\n    50â†’\n    51â†’```\n    52â†’workflow \"implement-feature\" {\n    53â†’  step code {\n    54â†’    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    55â†’    container {\n    56â†’      image = \"cloche/agent:latest\"\n    57â†’      network_allow = [\"docs.python.org\"]\n    58â†’    }\n    59â†’    results = [success, fail, retry_with_feedback]\n    60â†’  }\n    61â†’\n    62â†’  step check {\n    63â†’    run = \"make test && make lint\"\n    64â†’    results = [pass, fail]\n    65â†’  }\n    66â†’\n    67â†’  step review {\n    68â†’    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/review.md\")\n    69â†’    input = step.code.output\n    70â†’    results = [approved, changes_requested]\n    71â†’  }\n    72â†’\n    73â†’  // Wiring: step:result -> next_step\n    74â†’  code:success -> check\n    75â†’  code:fail -> abort\n    76â†’  code:retry_with_feedback -> code\n    77â†’\n    78â†’  check:pass -> review\n    79â†’  check:fail -> code:retry_with_feedback\n    80â†’\n    81â†’  review:approved -> done\n    82â†’  review:changes_requested -> code\n    83â†’}\n    84â†’```\n    85â†’\n    86â†’## Key Properties\n    87â†’\n    88â†’**Step type is inferred from content.** A `prompt` field makes it an agent step; a `run`\n    89â†’field makes it a script step.\n    90â†’\n    91â†’**Steps declare their possible results.** A step decides at runtime which result to\n    92â†’report. The graph engine follows the wiring to determine the next step.\n    93â†’\n    94â†’**Wiring is separate from step definitions.** This enables inserting new steps between\n    95â†’existing ones by rewiring â€” without modifying either step. This is the foundation for\n    96â†’Cloche's self-evolution feature.\n    97â†’\n    98â†’**Graphs are validated at parse time.** The parser checks that all declared results are\n    99â†’wired, no steps are orphaned, and an entry point exists.\n   100â†’\n   101â†’## Host Workflow Example\n   102â†’\n   103â†’```\n   104â†’# .cloche/host.cloche â€” runs on the host machine\n   105â†’workflow \"main\" {\n   106â†’  step prepare-prompt {\n   107â†’    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh\"\n   108â†’    results = [success, fail]\n   109â†’  }\n   110â†’\n   111â†’  step develop {\n   112â†’    workflow_name = \"develop\"\n   113â†’    prompt_step   = \"prepare-prompt\"\n   114â†’    results       = [success, fail]\n   115â†’  }\n   116â†’\n   117â†’  prepare-prompt:success -> develop\n   118â†’  prepare-prompt:fail    -> abort\n   119â†’  develop:success        -> done\n   120â†’  develop:fail           -> done\n   121â†’}\n   122â†’```\n   123â†’\n   124â†’The `workflow_name` step reads the prompt from the previous step's output (or\n   125â†’`prompt_step` override), dispatches a container workflow run, and blocks until it\n   126â†’completes.\n   127â†’\n   128â†’## Execution Model\n   129â†’\n   130â†’**Container workflows** are parsed and executed by `cloche-agent` inside a Docker\n   131â†’container. The agent walks the graph: execute current step, read its result, follow the\n   132â†’wiring to the next step. This continues until a terminal (`done` or `abort`) is reached.\n   133â†’All steps run inside the same container. File state accumulates naturally across steps.\n   134â†’\n   135â†’**Host workflows** are parsed and executed by the daemon on the host machine. Script\n   136â†’steps run via `sh -c`, and workflow steps dispatch container runs via the daemon's\n   137â†’standard run pipeline. Environment variables (`CLOCHE_TASK_ID`, `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR`,\n   138â†’etc.) are injected into each step.\n   139â†’"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9be06376-5a43-40f9-8380-030cf073c859","uuid":"88550078-ea2d-443a-ad1e-cd6b853689d7","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspace/docs/workflows.md","content":"# Workflows\n\nCloche workflows define a directed graph of steps connected by named results.\n\n## Workflow Locations\n\nCloche distinguishes two workflow locations based on the file they live in:\n\n**Container workflows** (`.cloche/*.cloche` except `host.cloche`) â€” Run inside a Docker\ncontainer via `cloche-agent`. Steps may only be `agent` or `script` type. These are the\nstandard workflows for coding tasks.\n\n**Host workflow** (`.cloche/host.cloche`) â€” Runs on the host machine as the daemon\nprocess. Steps may be `agent`, `script`, or `workflow` type. The `workflow` step type\ndispatches a container workflow run and waits for it to complete. This is the extension\npoint for custom orchestration strategies.\n\nThe convention is enforced at parse time: a `workflow_name` step in a container workflow\nfile is a parse error.\n\n## Concepts\n\n| Concept  | Description                                                        |\n|----------|--------------------------------------------------------------------|\n| workflow | A named graph of steps connected by result wiring                  |\n| step     | A unit of work (inferred: `prompt` = agent, `run` = script)        |\n| result   | A named outcome reported by a step (e.g. \"success\", \"fail\")       |\n| wiring   | Maps a step's result to the next step                              |\n| done     | Built-in terminal step â€” successful completion                     |\n| abort    | Built-in terminal step â€” failure with error reporting              |\n\n## Step Types\n\nStep type is inferred from the fields present in the step body:\n\n**agent** (has `prompt`) â€” Invokes a coding agent (Claude Code, or any tool conforming\nto the agent adapter interface) with a prompt. The agent works autonomously inside the\ncontainer. Available in both host and container workflows.\n\n**script** (has `run`) â€” Runs a shell command. Used for tests, linters, validators, or\nany deterministic check. Available in both host and container workflows.\n\n**workflow** (has `workflow_name`) â€” Dispatches a named container workflow run and blocks\nuntil it completes. Only available in host workflows (`host.cloche`).\n\nA step with more than one of `prompt`, `run`, or `workflow_name`, or none of them, is a\nparse error.\n\n## DSL Syntax\n\n```\nworkflow \"implement-feature\" {\n  step code {\n    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    container {\n      image = \"cloche/agent:latest\"\n      network_allow = [\"docs.python.org\"]\n    }\n    results = [success, fail, retry_with_feedback]\n  }\n\n  step check {\n    run = \"make test && make lint\"\n    results = [pass, fail]\n  }\n\n  step review {\n    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/review.md\")\n    input = step.code.output\n    results = [approved, changes_requested]\n  }\n\n  // Wiring: step:result -> next_step\n  code:success -> check\n  code:fail -> abort\n  code:retry_with_feedback -> code\n\n  check:pass -> review\n  check:fail -> code:retry_with_feedback\n\n  review:approved -> done\n  review:changes_requested -> code\n}\n```\n\n## Key Properties\n\n**Step type is inferred from content.** A `prompt` field makes it an agent step; a `run`\nfield makes it a script step.\n\n**Steps declare their possible results.** A step decides at runtime which result to\nreport. The graph engine follows the wiring to determine the next step.\n\n**Wiring is separate from step definitions.** This enables inserting new steps between\nexisting ones by rewiring â€” without modifying either step. This is the foundation for\nCloche's self-evolution feature.\n\n**Graphs are validated at parse time.** The parser checks that all declared results are\nwired, no steps are orphaned, and an entry point exists.\n\n## Host Workflow Example\n\n```\n# .cloche/host.cloche â€” runs on the host machine\nworkflow \"main\" {\n  step prepare-prompt {\n    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh\"\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  step develop {\n    workflow_name = \"develop\"\n    prompt_step   = \"prepare-prompt\"\n    results       = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  prepare-prompt:success -> develop\n  prepare-prompt:fail    -> abort\n  develop:success        -> done\n  develop:fail           -> done\n}\n```\n\nThe `workflow_name` step reads the prompt from the previous step's output (or\n`prompt_step` override), dispatches a container workflow run, and blocks until it\ncompletes.\n\n## Execution Model\n\n**Container workflows** are parsed and executed by `cloche-agent` inside a Docker\ncontainer. The agent walks the graph: execute current step, read its result, follow the\nwiring to the next step. This continues until a terminal (`done` or `abort`) is reached.\nAll steps run inside the same container. File state accumulates naturally across steps.\n\n**Host workflows** are parsed and executed by the daemon on the host machine. Script\nsteps run via `sh -c`, and workflow steps dispatch container runs via the daemon's\nstandard run pipeline. Environment variables (`CLOCHE_TASK_ID`, `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR`,\netc.) are injected into each step.\n","numLines":139,"startLine":1,"totalLines":139}}}
