[2026-03-09T21:13:29Z] [llm] {"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01E6QSBm1b9b1fZc4aff2GHe","type":"tool_result","content":"     1â†’# Cloche System Design\n     2â†’\n     3â†’## Overview\n     4â†’\n     5â†’Cloche is a system for grow-coding high quality applications. It provides containerized\n     6â†’environments for coding agents to operate in isolation, a workflow DSL for linking\n     7â†’agentic and script-driven tasks, validated code pipelines, and self-evolving tooling.\n     8â†’\n     9â†’This document describes the architecture for the MVP (v0.1).\n    10â†’\n    11â†’## System Components\n    12â†’\n    13â†’Cloche is a Go monorepo producing three binaries:\n    14â†’\n    15â†’```\n    16â†’cmd/\n    17â†’  cloche/         # CLI client (short-lived)\n    18â†’  cloched/        # Daemon/orchestrator (long-running)\n    19â†’  cloche-agent/   # In-container entrypoint (autonomous)\n    20â†’```\n    21â†’\n    22â†’### cloche (CLI)\n    23â†’\n    24â†’Short-lived process. Talks to `cloched` over gRPC (Unix socket locally, TCP remotely).\n    25â†’\n    26â†’Subcommands:\n    27â†’- `run <workflow>` â€” Launch a new workflow run\n    28â†’- `status [run-id]` â€” Check run status\n    29â†’- `logs <run-id>` â€” Stream logs from a running workflow (bidirectional gRPC stream)\n    30â†’- `stop <run-id>` â€” Cancel a running workflow (signals container with SIGTERM)\n    31â†’\n    32â†’Accepts prompt files or stdin input for user commands.\n    33â†’\n    34â†’### cloched (Daemon)\n    35â†’\n    36â†’Long-running process. Responsibilities:\n    37â†’- Launch and manage Docker containers for workflow runs\n    38â†’- Listen to status streams from running agents\n    39â†’- Record captures (step inputs, outputs, results, logs)\n    40â†’- Expose gRPC API for the CLI\n    41â†’- Persist state via pluggable storage (SQLite initially)\n    42â†’\n    43â†’The daemon does NOT interpret workflow logic. It knows \"container X is running workflow Y\"\n    44â†’and collects status. The agent is self-directing.\n    45â†’\n    46â†’### cloche-agent (In-Container Runtime)\n    47â†’\n    48â†’Autonomous process running inside the Docker container. Responsibilities:\n    49â†’- Parse the workflow DSL (workflow files live in the codebase)\n    50â†’- Walk the workflow graph, executing steps and following results\n    51â†’- Invoke coding agents (Claude Code, custom commands) and scripts\n    52â†’- Stream structured status events back to `cloched`\n    53â†’- Run to completion (`done` or `abort`) without human intervention\n    54â†’\n    55â†’The agent is told which workflow to execute at launch. It handles everything else.\n    56â†’\n    57â†’## Communication\n    58â†’\n    59â†’### CLI <-> Daemon: gRPC\n    60â†’\n    61â†’- Protobuf contracts define the API (the API is the spec)\n    62â†’- Bidirectional streaming for `logs` (tail container output in real-time)\n    63â†’- Unix socket for local communication, TCP for remote\n    64â†’\n    65â†’### Agent <-> Daemon: Structured JSON over stdout\n    66â†’\n    67â†’- The agent writes JSON-lines to stdout with status updates\n    68â†’- `cloched` attaches to the container's stdout stream via Docker API\n    69â†’- Messages include: step started, step completed (with result name), logs, errors\n    70â†’- Kill/cancel: daemon sends SIGTERM to container, agent handles graceful shutdown\n    71â†’\n    72â†’## Workflow DSL\n    73â†’\n    74â†’### Vocabulary\n    75â†’\n    76â†’| Concept  | Description                                                        |\n    77â†’|----------|--------------------------------------------------------------------|\n    78â†’| workflow | A named graph of steps connected by result wiring                  |\n    79â†’| step     | A unit of work (type: `agent` or `script`)                         |\n    80â†’| result   | A named outcome reported by a step (e.g. \"success\", \"fail\")       |"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9be06376-5a43-40f9-8380-030cf073c859","uuid":"96426f63-78ed-4e2b-8805-80f14636480d","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspace/docs/plans/2026-02-20-cloche-system-design.md","content":"# Cloche System Design\n\n## Overview\n\nCloche is a system for grow-coding high quality applications. It provides containerized\nenvironments for coding agents to operate in isolation, a workflow DSL for linking\nagentic and script-driven tasks, validated code pipelines, and self-evolving tooling.\n\nThis document describes the architecture for the MVP (v0.1).\n\n## System Components\n\nCloche is a Go monorepo producing three binaries:\n\n```\ncmd/\n  cloche/         # CLI client (short-lived)\n  cloched/        # Daemon/orchestrator (long-running)\n  cloche-agent/   # In-container entrypoint (autonomous)\n```\n\n### cloche (CLI)\n\nShort-lived process. Talks to `cloched` over gRPC (Unix socket locally, TCP remotely).\n\nSubcommands:\n- `run <workflow>` â€” Launch a new workflow run\n- `status [run-id]` â€” Check run status\n- `logs <run-id>` â€” Stream logs from a running workflow (bidirectional gRPC stream)\n- `stop <run-id>` â€” Cancel a running workflow (signals container with SIGTERM)\n\nAccepts prompt files or stdin input for user commands.\n\n### cloched (Daemon)\n\nLong-running process. Responsibilities:\n- Launch and manage Docker containers for workflow runs\n- Listen to status streams from running agents\n- Record captures (step inputs, outputs, results, logs)\n- Expose gRPC API for the CLI\n- Persist state via pluggable storage (SQLite initially)\n\nThe daemon does NOT interpret workflow logic. It knows \"container X is running workflow Y\"\nand collects status. The agent is self-directing.\n\n### cloche-agent (In-Container Runtime)\n\nAutonomous process running inside the Docker container. Responsibilities:\n- Parse the workflow DSL (workflow files live in the codebase)\n- Walk the workflow graph, executing steps and following results\n- Invoke coding agents (Claude Code, custom commands) and scripts\n- Stream structured status events back to `cloched`\n- Run to completion (`done` or `abort`) without human intervention\n\nThe agent is told which workflow to execute at launch. It handles everything else.\n\n## Communication\n\n### CLI <-> Daemon: gRPC\n\n- Protobuf contracts define the API (the API is the spec)\n- Bidirectional streaming for `logs` (tail container output in real-time)\n- Unix socket for local communication, TCP for remote\n\n### Agent <-> Daemon: Structured JSON over stdout\n\n- The agent writes JSON-lines to stdout with status updates\n- `cloched` attaches to the container's stdout stream via Docker API\n- Messages include: step started, step completed (with result name), logs, errors\n- Kill/cancel: daemon sends SIGTERM to container, agent handles graceful shutdown\n\n## Workflow DSL\n\n### Vocabulary\n\n| Concept  | Description                                                        |\n|----------|--------------------------------------------------------------------|\n| workflow | A named graph of steps connected by result wiring                  |\n| step     | A unit of work (type: `agent` or `script`)                         |\n| result   | A named outcome reported by a step (e.g. \"success\", \"fail\")       |","numLines":80,"startLine":1,"totalLines":252}}}
